- VSCode Version: 1.8.1
- OS Version: macOS Sierra 10.12.2

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Create the following C# code:
``` cs
namespace MyTest
{
    public interface ITest
    {
        // Random comment 1
        int Test1 { get; set; }

        int Test2 { get; set; } // Random comment 2


        int Test3 { get; set; }
        // Random comment 3
    }
}
```
2. See the screenshot below. I would expect `// Random comment 2` to be coloured green, similar to comments 1 and 3.
<img width="487" alt="comments" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5115488/22010477/b8e59a64-dc89-11e6-8b52-10fa7923b883.png">

- VSCode Version: Version 1.9.0-insider (1.9.0-insider) 217f96222ed0c8fc8693d85c6a2ed8e0c9ca35a1
- OS Version: macOS Sierra 10.12

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Create an extension with the following code
```javascript
  let vscode = require('vscode');
  let window = vscode.window;

  window.activeTextEditor.setDecorations(
    window.createTextEditorDecorationType({
      isWholeLine: true, // not relevant, but present in the real-world scenario
    }),
    [{
      range: new vscode.Range(0, 0, 0, 3),
      renderOptions: {after: {contentText: '+test'}}
    }]
  );
```
2. Open a text file with a single line `abc` in it.
3. No decoration is rendered:
<img width="149" alt="screen shot 2017-01-17 at 4 40 49 pm" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/979966/22010254/cbdf43fa-dcd3-11e6-9630-4d39b2f8dbd4.png">

The same code in Version 1.8.1 works as expected:
<img width="158" alt="screen shot 2017-01-17 at 4 40 23 pm" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/979966/22010250/c76c7d2e-dcd3-11e6-9009-7fb1e88cb108.png">

`before` is working (changing `renderOptions: {after:...` to `renderOptions: {before:...` renders the decoration), so it's just `after` that is broken.

Intellisense is not working inside the nested-intilializer block

- VSCode Version: 1.8.1 Commit ee428b0eead68bf0fb99ab5fdc4439be227b6281
- OS Version: Ubuntu 16.04

Steps to Reproduce:

```csharp
    public class Order {
        public Customer Customer { get; set; }
    }

    public class Customer {
        public string Name { get; set; }
        public string Age { get; set; }
    }

    public class App 
    {
        static void Main()
        {
            var o = new Order { Customer = new Customer {
               Name = "John"  // intellisense NOT working inside this block, it is not suggest the Name or Age
            }};
        }
    }
```

- VSCode Version: Insiders `217f96222ed0c8fc8693d85c6a2ed8e0c9ca35a1`
- OS Version: Mac OSX 10.11

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Paste the following code in a .js file: 
```
define( function()
{
    function bar()
    {

    };

    _.extend( Blah.prototype, 
    {
        foo : function(){
            var foobar = 'foobar';
            return foobar;
        }
    } );
} );
```
2. Notice how the syntax highlighting is broken.
3. The highlighting seems to work correctly if the brace on line 2 is moved up to the end of line 1.

